    id: 'Y8N12',
    title: 'Screen Time: Are We Asking the Wrong Question?',
    type: 'nonfiction',
    source: 'Original (factually grounded)',
    text: 'Every few months, a new report surfaces warning that teenagers are spending too many hours staring at screens. Politicians demand action. Parents share alarming statistics on — where else? — social media. And yet the more closely researchers examine the evidence, the more it seems we have been asking entirely the wrong question.\n\nThe idea that screen time is, by definition, harmful rests on a surprisingly thin foundation. A widely cited 2019 analysis by Oxford researchers Andrew Przybylski and Amy Orben found that the association between screen use and adolescent well-being is about as significant as the effect of wearing glasses or eating potatoes. Their paper, published in the prestigious journal Psychological Science, argued that the moral panic around screens is disproportionate to the actual evidence. Critics pushed back, but the core finding has proved robust: it is not how long young people spend on screens that matters most, but what they are doing while there.\n\nConsider the difference between two teenagers who each spend three hours online. The first is video-calling friends, editing a short film, playing a strategy game that requires sustained problem-solving, and checking the news. The second is passively scrolling through algorithmically curated content designed by engineers in Silicon Valley to maximise the time spent on the platform. Both register as "three hours of screen time" in any parental monitoring app. Yet intuitively — and, increasingly, empirically — these experiences are worlds apart.\n\nPlatform design, not duration, is the real villain. Social media companies employ hundreds of behavioural scientists to study how to keep users engaged. Features such as infinite scroll, notification badges, and variable reward mechanisms (you never know whether your next swipe will bring something exciting or dull) are borrowed directly from the psychology of gambling. Instagram\'s own internal research, leaked in 2021, showed that the platform knew its services made body image issues worse for a significant proportion of teenage girls. Knowing this, it continued. Duration limits imposed by parents do little to change the underlying architecture of addiction.\n\nNone of this is to say that excessive screen use carries no risks. Sleep disruption caused by blue-light exposure and the anxiety of constant social comparison are genuine concerns supported by evidence. But the solution is not simply to confiscate devices or impose blunt hourly caps. That approach treats the symptom and ignores the disease. What is needed is meaningful regulation of platform design: mandatory transparency about algorithmic amplification, restrictions on the use of behavioural manipulation techniques with users under eighteen, and a legal duty of care on platforms whose products demonstrably harm young people.\n\nUntil regulators catch up, the burden falls unfairly on individuals. Asking teenagers to resist platforms engineered by armies of PhD-holding psychologists is like asking someone to stay on a diet while locked in a sweet shop. It is not a failure of willpower; it is a failure of policy. The question is not how many hours young people spend online — it is who is responsible for what happens while they are there.',
