        model: 'Model answer: The writer uses the extended metaphor of bridges as "the circulatory system of civilisation" to elevate engineering from a technical activity to a matter of life and death — just as blocked arteries threaten the body, failing bridges threaten society. This makes the maintenance crisis feel urgent rather than merely administrative. The personification "the bridge effectively watches itself" is quietly striking: it suggests that modern engineering has created structures with a kind of awareness, which is both reassuring and slightly uncanny. Technical terms such as "accelerometers," "strain gauges," and "fibre-optic cables" are used without excessive explanation, which lends authority to the writing and treats the reader as intelligent, drawing them into the world of the engineer.'
