        model: 'Model answer: The writer opens with a vivid historical narrative — the collapse of Galloping Gertie — which immediately establishes stakes and draws the reader in through storytelling before any technical explanation begins. This is a deliberate structural choice: the drama of 1940 frames the entire article as a story of lessons learned. The piece then moves chronologically and thematically, from universal engineering principles to the Millau Viaduct\'s achievements, to the cutting-edge sensor technology of the Queensferry Crossing. This ascending structure creates a sense of growing confidence in human ingenuity — before the Minneapolis bridge collapse abruptly disrupts it. By placing this tragedy after the technological achievements, the writer creates a stark contrast: the same civilisation that builds "thinking bridges" cannot maintain its older ones. The final paragraph resolves this tension not by dismissing the achievements but by calling for "will to maintain them," making the ending feel purposeful rather than defeatist.'
