        model: 'Model answer: The writer uses cold statistics to devastating effect. The statement that K2 has "a death rate of approximately one in every four successful summits" is clinical and precise, and its matter-of-fact register makes the danger feel even more absolute — as if it is simply a fact of the universe, not a dramatic warning. The phrase "the Death Zone" operates differently: its capitalisation transforms a geographic description into something almost mythological, signalling that this is territory where normal rules no longer apply. Most powerfully, the environments are described as "indifferent to human presence," stripping away any romantic notion of nature as a worthy adversary. They are not dangerous because they are hostile; they are dangerous because they simply do not care. This philosophical framing is more unsettling than any dramatic description of storms or frostbite.'
