    text: 'The average person in the United Kingdom encounters between three thousand and ten thousand advertising messages every single day. They appear on the sides of buses, inside smartphone apps, on the packaging of every product in the supermarket, woven into the content of YouTube videos, and now — through personalised targeting — tailored precisely to individual anxieties, desires, and browsing habits. Most of us believe we are unaffected by advertising. The research suggests we are mistaken.\n\nModern advertising rarely tries to sell a product. It tries to sell a feeling. Nike does not advertise trainers; it advertises the sensation of becoming extraordinary. Coca-Cola does not advertise a fizzy drink; it advertises happiness, friendship, and the warm light of summer evenings. This shift — from product to emotion — began in earnest in the 1950s with the work of American psychologist Ernest Dichter, who pioneered what he called "motivational research": the systematic study of the unconscious desires that drive purchasing decisions. Dichter advised brands to connect their products to deep psychological needs — belonging, self-esteem, identity — rather than to functional features. The industry has never looked back.\n\nThe digital revolution has made Dichter\'s insights terrifyingly precise. Every click, pause, scroll, and purchase generates data that algorithms use to build a detailed psychological profile of each user. Facebook\'s parent company Meta has patented technology that can infer a user\'s emotional state from the way they interact with their phone — typing speed, error frequency, the duration of pauses between messages. Advertisers can then target individuals at the moments when they are most emotionally vulnerable: lonely at midnight, anxious before a job interview, or bored and seeking stimulation. This is not advertising in the traditional sense; it is behavioural manipulation at scale.\n\nChildren are a particular concern. Research by the American Psychological Association found that children under eight years old cannot reliably distinguish between advertising content and editorial content. They process a persuasive message from a favourite cartoon character with the same trust they give a parent. Yet advertising to children is a multi-billion-pound industry. Unboxing videos on YouTube — in which children watch other children open toys — attract hundreds of millions of views. Many are funded by toy manufacturers. Some feature child influencers who are, in effect, paid brand ambassadors, though the commercial relationship is not always disclosed.\n\nThe advertising industry defends itself with two arguments: that advertising funds the free content we all enjoy, and that informed consumers can choose to ignore it. Both claims deserve scrutiny. The first is partially true — advertising does subsidise journalism, social media, and entertainment — but this does not make the methods used to maximise engagement ethically neutral. The second claim rests on a fiction of rational choice that decades of behavioural economics have comprehensively dismantled. Consumers cannot "choose to ignore" messages they do not consciously register, delivered at moments engineered for maximum vulnerability.\n\nNone of this means that advertising is inherently evil, or that it cannot be creative, entertaining, and even useful in connecting people with products they genuinely want. But it does mean that the relationship between advertiser and audience is not a transaction between equals. The next time a brand makes you feel something, it is worth pausing to ask: did you choose that feeling, or was it chosen for you?',
